<img src="/sites/worldliteraturetoday.org/files/authors/ryan-long/longryan-b.jpg" alt width height border="1" />
<br/>
<div class="phototagleft">
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Ryan Long</strong> is professor of Spanish and comparative literature at the University of Maryland, College Park. He is the author of <em>Queer Exposures: Sexuality and Photography in the Fiction and Poetry of Roberto Bolaño</em> (Pittsburgh, 2021) and <em>Fictions of Totality: The Mexican Novel, 1968, and the National-Popular State</em> (Purdue, 2008). He is currently writing a book titled <em>The Poetics of Place and Displacement: Hannes Meyer and Postrevolutionary Mexico. He also </em>edits the Mexican prose fiction section of the <em>Handbook of Latin American Studies</em>. His recent publications include chapters in&nbsp;<em>Roberto Bolaño in Context</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>Women Photographers and Mexican Modernity</em>.&nbsp;His article about Emiliano Monge’s novel&nbsp;<em>Las tierras arrasadas</em>&nbsp;is forthcoming in the&nbsp;<em>Revista Canadiense de Estudios Hispánicos</em>.</p>
